4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, an individual commits the
6 crime of cruelty to a dog or cat when he or she takes
7 certain actions. The law also defines the term "cruel"
8 to include abandonment of a dog or cat for purposes of
9 committing this crime.
10 This bill would specifically prohibit the
11 abandonment of a dog or cat and provide a criminal
12 penalty for violating this prohibition.
13 This bill would also make nonsubstantive,
14 technical revisions to update the existing code
15 language to current style.
16
17
18 A BILL
19 TO BE ENTITLED
20 AN ACT
21
22 Relating to dogs and cats; to amend Sections 13A-11-240
23 and 13A-11-243, Code of Alabama 1975, to define the term
24 "abandon"; to provide for the enforcement of the crime of
25 abandonment of a dog or cat; to make nonsubstantive, technical
26 revisions to update the existing code language to current
27 style; to add Section 13A-11-241.1 to the Code of Alabama
28 1975, to prohibit a person from abandoning a dog or cat; and
Page 1

1975, to prohibit a person from abandoning a dog or cat; and
HB177 INTRODUCED
29 to provide criminal penalties for violations.
30 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
31 Section 1. Sections 13A-11-240 and 13A-11-243, Code of
32 Alabama 1975, are amended to read as follows:
33 "§13A-11-240
34 (a) The word "torture" as used in this article shall
35 mean theact of doing physical injury to a dog or cat by the
36 infliction of inhumane treatment or gross physical abuse meant
37 to cause said animal intensive or prolonged pain or serious
38 physical injury, or thereby causing death due to said act.
39 (b) The word "cruel" as used in this article shall
40 mean:
41 For purposes of this article, the following terms have
42 the following meanings:
43 (1) ABANDON. To forsake entirely or leave a dog or cat
44 at a location without providing minimum reasonable care.
45 (2) CRUEL. Every act, omission, or neglect, including
46 abandonment, where unnecessary or unjustifiable pain or
47 suffering, including abandonment, is caused or where
48 unnecessary pain or suffering is allowed to continue.
49 (c) The words "dog or cat" as used in this article
50 shall mean any(3) DOG or CAT. Any domesticated member of the
51 dog or cat family.
52 (4) TORTURE. The act of doing physical injury to a dog
53 or cat by the infliction of inhumane treatment or gross
54 physical abuse that causes the dog or cat intensive or
55 prolonged pain or serious physical injury, or thereby causing
56 death."
